Deployment and Service files are created for kubernetes deploymet 
servce is of Nodeport at port 30008
label and seletors of pod template are referenced inside the service seletor to get pod service

jenkins structure

1. Library files structure

(root)
+- src/                     # Standard Java/Groovy OOP classes
|  +- com
|     +- company
|        +- Utilities.groovy
+- vars/                    # Global variables and custom DSL steps (Most Common)
|  +- buildDocker.groovy    # Called in pipeline as: buildDocker()
|  +- buildDocker.txt       # Optional documentation for the step
+- resources/               # Static non-Groovy helper data (JSON, XML, templates)

2. Syntax Definig steps

// File: vars/sayHello.groovy
def call(String name) {
    echo "Hello, ${name}!"
}

Global steps are defined in the vars/ directory. 
The filename becomes the step name inside your pipeline. 
You must implement a call method inside the file.

Adavanced Map-Argument  syntax(vars/buildDocker.groovy)

// File: vars/buildDocker.groovy
def call(Map config = [:]) {
    // Access passed variables with default fallbacks
    def imageName = config.get('imageName', 'my-default-app')
    def tag = config.get('tag', 'latest')

    sh "docker build -t ${imageName}:${tag} ."
}

Once the library is configured in Jenkins (via Manage Jenkins -> System -> Global Pipeline Libraries), 
you use the global variables inside a Declarative or Scripted pipeline.Importing Specific VersionsDefault version: @Library('my-shared-library') _Specific Branch/Tag: @Library('my-shared-library@production') _Multiple Libraries: @Library(['lib-one', 'lib-two@1.2']) _
Example Implementationgroovy@Library('my-shared-library@main') _

pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Greet') {
            steps {
                // Calling the simple string step
                sayHello('Developer') 
            }
        }
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                // Calling the map-argument step
                buildDocker(
                    imageName: 'frontend-service',
                    tag: 'v1.0.0'
                )
            }
        }
    }
}

4. Syntax for Advanced Class Libraries (src/)If you prefer standard Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) over basic functional scripts, place code inside the src/ directory.Defining a Class (src/com/company/Helper.groovy)groovypackage com.company
import java.io.Serializable

// Classes used in pipelines must implement Serializable
class Helper implements Serializable {
    def steps
    
    // Pass pipeline context ('this') to access native steps like echo/sh
    Helper(steps) {
        this.steps = steps
    }

    def performCleanup() {
        steps.echo "Cleaning up workspace environment..."
        steps.cleanWs()
    }

Instantiating the Class (Jenkinsfile)groovy@Library('my-shared-library') _
import com.company.Helper

pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Clean') {
            steps {
                script {
                    // Instantiate class and pass 'this' as the pipeline context
                    def utils = new Helper(this)
                    utils.performCleanup()
                }
            }
        }
    }
}